With the types os these two insects before me, I am quite unable to separate them as distinct species; P. impromta merely differs from P. picticollis in having an in- distinct spot on either side of the median lobe of the prothorax at the base (often obsolete)‚ and the elytra a little more closely punctured. Boheman appears only to have seen female specimens ; the male has the elytra broader (at the base considerably wider than the prothorax) and shorter, with the humeri broadly rounded. We have received numerous examples of both sexes from VentanaS, in Western Mexico.
